[[File:Chino pants.jpg|thumb|170px|alt=Chino pants|A pair of trousers made from chino cloth, generally referred to as chinos]]
'''Chino cloth''' ({{IPAc-en|ˌ|t|ʃ|iː|n|əʊ}} {{respell|CHEE|noh}}) is a [[twill]] fabric, originally made of 100% [[cotton]]. The most common items made from it, [[trousers]], are widely called ''chinos''. Today it is also found in cotton-synthetic blends.

Developed in the mid-19th century for British and French military uniforms, it has since migrated into civilian wear. Trousers of such a fabric gained popularity in the U.S. when [[Spanish–American War]] veterans returned from the [[Philippines]] with their twill military trousers.

==Etymology==
The etymology of the term ''chino'' is disputed. Some sources identify the root as the [[Spanish language in the Americas|American Spanish]] language word ''chino'', which translated literally means [[toast]]ed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=chino |title=Online Etymology Dictionary |publisher=Etymonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-01}}</ref>  Because the cloth itself was originally manufactured in [[China]], the name of the trousers may have come from the country of origin.<ref name=duchamplondon1>{{cite web|title=The History Of The Chino|url=http://www.duchamplondon.com/marcs_blog/the-history-of-the-chino/|publisher=Duchamp London|accessdate=21 December 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012043922/http://www.duchamplondon.com/marcs_blog/the-history-of-the-chino/|archivedate=12 October 2013}}</ref>

==History==
First designed to be used in the military and then taken up by civilians, chino fabric was originally made to be simple, hard-wearing and comfortable for soldiers to wear; the use of natural earth-tone colors also began the move towards camouflage, instead of the brightly colored [[tunic]]s used prior. The British and then American armies started wearing it as standard during the latter half of the 1800s.<ref name="duchamplondon1" />

The pure-cotton fabric is widely used for trousers, referred to as chinos. The original [[khaki]] (light brown) is the traditional and most popular color, but chinos are made in many shades.<ref name="duchamplondon1" />

