{{L. Sprague de Camp}}
[[Category:1950 short stories]] [[Category:Procyon in fiction]] [[Category:Short stories by L. Sprague de Camp]] [[Category:Works originally published in Startling Stories]]

A '''reversible garment''' is a garment that can be worn two ways. There is no true "[[wikt:inside out|inside out]]" to a reversible garment, since either way, it gives a fashionable appearance.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Webster's II New College Dictionary|author1=Houghton Mifflin Company|author2=Webster|date=1999|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Company|isbn=9780395962145|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vsaXzwMndS8C|page=949|accessdate=2015-04-05}}</ref> Garments that are commonly made reversible include [[hat]]s, [[jacket]]s, [[vest]]s, [[sweater]]s, [[shirt]]s, [[trousers]], and [[skirt]]s.<ref name="freepatentsonline">{{cite web|url=http://www.freepatentsonline.com/7441281.html|title=Multi reversible garment - Salem, Tamara|publisher=freepatentsonline.com|accessdate=2015-04-05}}</ref><ref name="nytimes">{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/03/business/patents-mix-match-mix-match-keep-going.html|title=Patents - Mix, Match. Mix, Match. Keep Going. - NYTimes.com|publisher=nytimes.com|accessdate=2015-04-05}}</ref>

Reversible garments have some features unlike other types of garments, such as thicker overall fabric (since two fabric are often sewn together), [[button]]s on both sides (in garments that have buttons), different types of stitching, and no tags<ref name="google2">{{cite book|title=The Zapp Method of Couture Sewing: Tailor Garments Easily Using Any Pattern|author=Zapp, A.|date=2004|publisher=Krause Publications|isbn=9780873496810|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ATMc_oHvPfsC|pages=2–77|accessdate=2015-04-05}}</ref><ref>http://books.google.com/books?id=6gM9qmMOcW8C&pg=PA44&dq=%22reversible+garment%22&lr=&as_brr=3&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html{{Dead link|date=April 2015}}</ref>

Ancient [[shepherd]]s used to have reversible garments with a warm side that they would wear when the weather was cold, and a cool side when the weather was hot.<ref name="google3">{{cite book|title=Jeremiah: Volume 2: 26-52|author=McKane, W.|date=2000|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic|isbn=9780567097323|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=x--hxEWKUYgC|page=1059|accessdate=2015-04-05}}</ref>

